{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_0186KewU49cN8Yi9yNe2PjeV","type":"tool_result","content":"     1→import {\n     2→  Connection,\n     3→  Keypair,\n     4→  PublicKey,\n     5→  SystemProgram,\n     6→  Transaction,\n     7→  TransactionInstruction,\n     8→} from \"@solana/web3.js\";\n     9→import { deriveMatchPda } from \"./fairness.js\";\n    10→import { CoinflipIDL as coinflipIdl, LordofrngsIDL as lordIdl } from \"@rng-utopia/anchor-client\";\n    11→\n    12→export const COINFLIP_PROGRAM_ID = new PublicKey(coinflipIdl.address);\n    13→export const LORDOFRNGS_PROGRAM_ID = new PublicKey(lordIdl.address);\n    14→\n    15→function getInstructionDiscriminator(\n    16→  idl: { instructions: Array<{ name: string; discriminator: number[] }> },\n    17→  instructionName: string,\n    18→): Buffer {\n    19→  const instruction = idl.instructions.find((entry) => entry.name === instructionName);\n    20→  if (!instruction) {\n    21→    throw new Error(`Instruction ${instructionName} not found in IDL`);\n    22→  }\n    23→  return Buffer.from(instruction.discriminator);\n    24→}\n    25→\n    26→const CREATE_MATCH_DISCRIMINATOR = getInstructionDiscriminator(\n    27→  coinflipIdl,\n    28→  \"create_match\",\n    29→);\n    30→const CREATE_ROUND_DISCRIMINATOR = getInstructionDiscriminator(\n    31→  lordIdl,\n    32→  \"create_round\",\n    33→);\n    34→\n    35→/** Derive the coinflip config PDA (seeds: [\"coinflip_config\"]). */\n    36→function deriveConfigPda(): [PublicKey, number] {\n    37→  return PublicKey.findProgramAddressSync(\n    38→    [Buffer.from(\"coinflip_config\")],\n    39→    COINFLIP_PROGRAM_ID,\n    40→  );\n    41→}\n    42→\n    43→function deriveLordConfigPda(): [PublicKey, number] {\n    44→  return PublicKey.findProgramAddressSync(\n    45→    [Buffer.from(\"lord_config\")],\n    46→    LORDOFRNGS_PROGRAM_ID,\n    47→  );\n    48→}\n    49→\n    50→export function deriveLordRoundPda(matchId: Buffer): [PublicKey, number] {\n    51→  return PublicKey.findProgramAddressSync(\n    52→    [Buffer.from(\"jackpot_round\"), matchId],\n    53→    LORDOFRNGS_PROGRAM_ID,\n    54→  );\n    55→}\n    56→\n    57→/**\n    58→ * Borsh-encode the create_match instruction data.\n    59→ * Layout: discriminator(8) + commitment(32) + amount(8, u64 LE) + side(1) + matchId(8) = 57 bytes\n    60→ */\n    61→function encodeCreateMatchData(\n    62→  commitment: Buffer,\n    63→  amountLamports: number,\n    64→  side: number,\n    65→  matchId: Buffer,\n    66→): Buffer {\n    67→  const amount = Buffer.alloc(8);\n    68→  amount.writeBigUInt64LE(BigInt(amountLamports));\n    69→  return Buffer.concat([\n    70→    CREATE_MATCH_DISCRIMINATOR,\n    71→    commitment,\n    72→    amount,\n    73→    Buffer.from([side]),\n    74→    matchId,\n    75→  ]);\n    76→}\n    77→\n    78→function encodeCreateRoundData(\n    79→  commitment: Buffer,\n    80→  amountLamports: number,\n    81→  matchId: Buffer,\n    82→): Buffer {\n    83→  const amount = Buffer.alloc(8);\n    84→  amount.writeBigUInt64LE(BigInt(amountLamports));\n    85→  return Buffer.concat([CREATE_ROUND_DISCRIMINATOR, commitment, amount, matchId]);\n    86→}\n    87→\n    88→export interface BuildCreateMatchTxParams {\n    89→  connection: Connection;\n    90→  creator: PublicKey;\n    91→  serverKeypair: Keypair;\n    92→  commitment: Buffer;\n    93→  amountLamports: number;\n    94→  side: number;\n    95→  matchId: Buffer;\n    96→}\n    97→\n    98→export interface BuildCreateMatchTxResult {\n    99→  /** Base64-serialized partially-signed transaction. */\n   100→  transaction: string;\n   101→  /** The match PDA address. */\n   102→  matchPda: PublicKey;\n   103→  /** Block height limit paired with the pinned recent blockhash. */\n   104→  lastValidBlockHeight: number;\n   105→}\n   106→\n   107→export interface BuildCreateLordRoundTxParams {\n   108→  connection: Connection;\n   109→  creator: PublicKey;\n   110→  serverKeypair: Keypair;\n   111→  commitment: Buffer;\n   112→  amountLamports: number;\n   113→  matchId: Buffer;\n   114→}\n   115→\n   116→export interface BuildCreateLordRoundTxResult {\n   117→  transaction: string;\n   118→  roundPda: PublicKey;\n   119→  lastValidBlockHeight: number;\n   120→}\n   121→\n   122→/**\n   123→ * Build a `create_match` transaction, partially signed by the server.\n   124→ *\n   125→ * - Creator wallet is set as fee payer (server pays zero on-chain cost).\n   126→ * - Server keypair partially signs (as the `server: Signer` account).\n   127→ * - Recent blockhash is fetched at build time.\n   128→ * - Returns base64-serialized tx for the client to co-sign and submit.\n   129→ */\n   130→export async function buildCreateMatchTx(\n   131→  params: BuildCreateMatchTxParams,\n   132→): Promise<BuildCreateMatchTxResult> {\n   133→  const { connection, creator, serverKeypair, commitment, amountLamports, side, matchId } =\n   134→    params;\n   135→\n   136→  const [matchPda] = deriveMatchPda(creator, matchId);\n   137→  const [configPda] = deriveConfigPda();\n   138→\n   139→  const data = encodeCreateMatchData(commitment, amountLamports, side, matchId);\n   140→\n   141→  const tx = new Transaction();\n   142→\n   143→  tx.add(\n   144→    new TransactionInstruction({\n   145→    keys: [\n   146→      { pubkey: creator, isSigner: true, isWritable: true },\n   147→      { pubkey: serverKeypair.publicKey, isSigner: true, isWritable: false },\n   148→      { pubkey: matchPda, isSigner: false, isWritable: true },\n   149→      { pubkey: configPda, isSigner: false, isWritable: false },\n   150→      {\n   151→        pubkey: SystemProgram.programId,\n   152→        isSigner: false,\n   153→        isWritable: false,\n   154→      },\n   155→    ],\n   156→    programId: COINFLIP_PROGRAM_ID,\n   157→    data,\n   158→    }),\n   159→  );\n   160→\n   161→  const { blockhash, lastValidBlockHeight } =\n   162→    await connection.getLatestBlockhash();\n   163→\n   164→  tx.feePayer = creator;\n   165→  tx.recentBlockhash = blockhash;\n   166→  tx.lastValidBlockHeight = lastValidBlockHeight;\n   167→\n   168→  // Partially sign with server keypair only — creator signs client-side\n   169→  tx.partialSign(serverKeypair);\n   170→\n   171→  const serialized = tx\n   172→    .serialize({ requireAllSignatures: false })\n   173→    .toString(\"base64\");\n   174→\n   175→  return { transaction: serialized, matchPda, lastValidBlockHeight };\n   176→}\n   177→\n   178→export async function buildCreateLordRoundTx(\n   179→  params: BuildCreateLordRoundTxParams,\n   180→): Promise<BuildCreateLordRoundTxResult> {\n   181→  const { connection, creator, serverKeypair, commitment, amountLamports, matchId } =\n   182→    params;\n   183→\n   184→  const [roundPda] = deriveLordRoundPda(matchId);\n   185→  const [configPda] = deriveLordConfigPda();\n   186→  const data = encodeCreateRoundData(commitment, amountLamports, matchId);\n   187→\n   188→  const tx = new Transaction();\n   189→  tx.add(\n   190→    new TransactionInstruction({\n   191→      keys: [\n   192→        { pubkey: creator, isSigner: true, isWritable: true },\n   193→        { pubkey: serverKeypair.publicKey, isSigner: true, isWritable: true }, // pays rent\n   194→        { pubkey: configPda, isSigner: false, isWritable: false },\n   195→        { pubkey: roundPda, isSigner: false, isWritable: true },\n   196→        { pubkey: SystemProgram.programId, isSigner: false, isWritable: false },\n   197→      ],\n   198→      programId: LORDOFRNGS_PROGRAM_ID,\n   199→      data,\n   200→    }),\n   201→  );\n   202→\n   203→  const { blockhash, lastValidBlockHeight } = await connection.getLatestBlockhash();\n   204→\n   205→  tx.feePayer = creator;\n   206→  tx.recentBlockhash = blockhash;\n   207→  tx.lastValidBlockHeight = lastValidBlockHeight;\n   208→  tx.partialSign(serverKeypair);\n   209→\n   210→  const serialized = tx\n   211→    .serialize({ requireAllSignatures: false })\n   212→    .toString(\"base64\");\n   213→\n   214→  return { transaction: serialized, roundPda, lastValidBlockHeight };\n   215→}\n   216→"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"3173b348-180a-4cf2-ac38-47c17bdb617e","uuid":"8c3d9370-8572-4e99-8e12-918883f2578b","tool_use_result":{"type":"text","file":{"filePath":"/workspaces/rng-utopia/sources/rng-utopia/services/backend/src/tx-builder.ts","content":"import {\n  Connection,\n  Keypair,\n  PublicKey,\n  SystemProgram,\n  Transaction,\n  TransactionInstruction,\n} from \"@solana/web3.js\";\nimport { deriveMatchPda } from \"./fairness.js\";\nimport { CoinflipIDL as coinflipIdl, LordofrngsIDL as lordIdl } from \"@rng-utopia/anchor-client\";\n\nexport const COINFLIP_PROGRAM_ID = new PublicKey(coinflipIdl.address);\nexport const LORDOFRNGS_PROGRAM_ID = new PublicKey(lordIdl.address);\n\nfunction getInstructionDiscriminator(\n  idl: { instructions: Array<{ name: string; discriminator: number[] }> },\n  instructionName: string,\n): Buffer {\n  const instruction = idl.instructions.find((entry) => entry.name === instructionName);\n  if (!instruction) {\n    throw new Error(`Instruction ${instructionName} not found in IDL`);\n  }\n  return Buffer.from(instruction.discriminator);\n}\n\nconst CREATE_MATCH_DISCRIMINATOR = getInstructionDiscriminator(\n  coinflipIdl,\n  \"create_match\",\n);\nconst CREATE_ROUND_DISCRIMINATOR = getInstructionDiscriminator(\n  lordIdl,\n  \"create_round\",\n);\n\n/** Derive the coinflip config PDA (seeds: [\"coinflip_config\"]). */\nfunction deriveConfigPda(): [PublicKey, number] {\n  return PublicKey.findProgramAddressSync(\n    [Buffer.from(\"coinflip_config\")],\n    COINFLIP_PROGRAM_ID,\n  );\n}\n\nfunction deriveLordConfigPda(): [PublicKey, number] {\n  return PublicKey.findProgramAddressSync(\n    [Buffer.from(\"lord_config\")],\n    LORDOFRNGS_PROGRAM_ID,\n  );\n}\n\nexport function deriveLordRoundPda(matchId: Buffer): [PublicKey, number] {\n  return PublicKey.findProgramAddressSync(\n    [Buffer.from(\"jackpot_round\"), matchId],\n    LORDOFRNGS_PROGRAM_ID,\n  );\n}\n\n/**\n * Borsh-encode the create_match instruction data.\n * Layout: discriminator(8) + commitment(32) + amount(8, u64 LE) + side(1) + matchId(8) = 57 bytes\n */\nfunction encodeCreateMatchData(\n  commitment: Buffer,\n  amountLamports: number,\n  side: number,\n  matchId: Buffer,\n): Buffer {\n  const amount = Buffer.alloc(8);\n  amount.writeBigUInt64LE(BigInt(amountLamports));\n  return Buffer.concat([\n    CREATE_MATCH_DISCRIMINATOR,\n    commitment,\n    amount,\n    Buffer.from([side]),\n    matchId,\n  ]);\n}\n\nfunction encodeCreateRoundData(\n  commitment: Buffer,\n  amountLamports: number,\n  matchId: Buffer,\n): Buffer {\n  const amount = Buffer.alloc(8);\n  amount.writeBigUInt64LE(BigInt(amountLamports));\n  return Buffer.concat([CREATE_ROUND_DISCRIMINATOR, commitment, amount, matchId]);\n}\n\nexport interface BuildCreateMatchTxParams {\n  connection: Connection;\n  creator: PublicKey;\n  serverKeypair: Keypair;\n  commitment: Buffer;\n  amountLamports: number;\n  side: number;\n  matchId: Buffer;\n}\n\nexport interface BuildCreateMatchTxResult {\n  /** Base64-serialized partially-signed transaction. */\n  transaction: string;\n  /** The match PDA address. */\n  matchPda: PublicKey;\n  /** Block height limit paired with the pinned recent blockhash. */\n  lastValidBlockHeight: number;\n}\n\nexport interface BuildCreateLordRoundTxParams {\n  connection: Connection;\n  creator: PublicKey;\n  serverKeypair: Keypair;\n  commitment: Buffer;\n  amountLamports: number;\n  matchId: Buffer;\n}\n\nexport interface BuildCreateLordRoundTxResult {\n  transaction: string;\n  roundPda: PublicKey;\n  lastValidBlockHeight: number;\n}\n\n/**\n * Build a `create_match` transaction, partially signed by the server.\n *\n * - Creator wallet is set as fee payer (server pays zero on-chain cost).\n * - Server keypair partially signs (as the `server: Signer` account).\n * - Recent blockhash is fetched at build time.\n * - Returns base64-serialized tx for the client to co-sign and submit.\n */\nexport async function buildCreateMatchTx(\n  params: BuildCreateMatchTxParams,\n): Promise<BuildCreateMatchTxResult> {\n  const { connection, creator, serverKeypair, commitment, amountLamports, side, matchId } =\n    params;\n\n  const [matchPda] = deriveMatchPda(creator, matchId);\n  const [configPda] = deriveConfigPda();\n\n  const data = encodeCreateMatchData(commitment, amountLamports, side, matchId);\n\n  const tx = new Transaction();\n\n  tx.add(\n    new TransactionInstruction({\n    keys: [\n      { pubkey: creator, isSigner: true, isWritable: true },\n      { pubkey: serverKeypair.publicKey, isSigner: true, isWritable: false },\n      { pubkey: matchPda, isSigner: false, isWritable: true },\n      { pubkey: configPda, isSigner: false, isWritable: false },\n      {\n        pubkey: SystemProgram.programId,\n        isSigner: false,\n        isWritable: false,\n      },\n    ],\n    programId: COINFLIP_PROGRAM_ID,\n    data,\n    }),\n  );\n\n  const { blockhash, lastValidBlockHeight } =\n    await connection.getLatestBlockhash();\n\n  tx.feePayer = creator;\n  tx.recentBlockhash = blockhash;\n  tx.lastValidBlockHeight = lastValidBlockHeight;\n\n  // Partially sign with server keypair only — creator signs client-side\n  tx.partialSign(serverKeypair);\n\n  const serialized = tx\n    .serialize({ requireAllSignatures: false })\n    .toString(\"base64\");\n\n  return { transaction: serialized, matchPda, lastValidBlockHeight };\n}\n\nexport async function buildCreateLordRoundTx(\n  params: BuildCreateLordRoundTxParams,\n): Promise<BuildCreateLordRoundTxResult> {\n  const { connection, creator, serverKeypair, commitment, amountLamports, matchId } =\n    params;\n\n  const [roundPda] = deriveLordRoundPda(matchId);\n  const [configPda] = deriveLordConfigPda();\n  const data = encodeCreateRoundData(commitment, amountLamports, matchId);\n\n  const tx = new Transaction();\n  tx.add(\n    new TransactionInstruction({\n      keys: [\n        { pubkey: creator, isSigner: true, isWritable: true },\n        { pubkey: serverKeypair.publicKey, isSigner: true, isWritable: true }, // pays rent\n        { pubkey: configPda, isSigner: false, isWritable: false },\n        { pubkey: roundPda, isSigner: false, isWritable: true },\n        { pubkey: SystemProgram.programId, isSigner: false, isWritable: false },\n      ],\n      programId: LORDOFRNGS_PROGRAM_ID,\n      data,\n    }),\n  );\n\n  const { blockhash, lastValidBlockHeight } = await connection.getLatestBlockhash();\n\n  tx.feePayer = creator;\n  tx.recentBlockhash = blockhash;\n  tx.lastValidBlockHeight = lastValidBlockHeight;\n  tx.partialSign(serverKeypair);\n\n  const serialized = tx\n    .serialize({ requireAllSignatures: false })\n    .toString(\"base64\");\n\n  return { transaction: serialized, roundPda, lastValidBlockHeight };\n}\n","numLines":216,"startLine":1,"totalLines":216}}}
{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-opus-4-6","id":"msg_0162ZEThUjNXfjSmcLaopz8p","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Now I have a thorough understanding of the existing code patterns. Let me also quickly check what the closecall IDL instructions look like to understand the exact account order.\n\nI need to read the closecall IDL to get the discriminators and exact account order. Let me look at the key parts.\n\nFrom my exploration, I know:\n- `create_round` accounts: server, config, round, price_update, system_program\n- `settle_round` accounts: caller, round, config, price_update, treasury, rent_receiver + remaining_accounts\n- `timeout_refund` accounts: caller, round, config, rent_receiver + remaining_accounts\n\n\n- All instructions take just a `round_id` as the argument\n\nSo I need to implement three functions in `settle-tx.ts`: `buildCreateRoundTx` to construct the create_round instruction, `buildSettleRoundTx` to handle settlement with winner accounts, and `buildTimeoutRefundTx` for refunds. The main difference from the other games is that this uses oracle-based pricing instead of a commit-reveal scheme.\n\nSince the server handles everything—creating rounds, settling them, and processing refunds—it's both the fee payer and signer for all transactions. The Pyth price account replaces the slot_hashes reference, and I'll need to pass remaining_accounts for the batch payouts and refunds. Let me start building out the implementation.\n\nThe key difference from coinflip and lord is that there's no commit-reveal mechanism here—the server constructs and signs the complete transaction directly. The functions I need to implement are transaction builders that return signed transactions for the clock worker to submit later, rather than full settlement flows that handle submission and confirmation themselves.\n\nBuilding the transaction builders... Tx` and `buildCreateLordRoundTx` in tx-builder.ts return a partially-signed tx for client co-signing\n\nFor closecall, the server builds and sends everything. The clock worker will call these builders, send the tx, and handle DB updates. So the builders should return a Transaction ready for the server to sign and send.\n\nActually, looking more carefully at the spec, it says to put these in `settle-tx.ts`. Let me think about what the right interface is.\n\nThe clock worker will need:\n1. `buildCreateRoundTx` - creates a new round with open price from Pyth\n2. `buildSettleRoundTx` - settles a round, distributing payouts\n3. `buildTimeoutRefundTx` - refunds all players when deadline passed\n\nThese should be transaction builders that take the necessary params and return a Transaction object ready for the server to sign and send.\n\nNow I'm checking the IDL to get the exact account ordering for each instruction. From my earlier exploration, I have the account structure for create_round (server as signer and payer, config PDA, new round PDA, Pyth price update, and system program) and settle_round (caller as signer, round PDA to close, config PDA, and Pyth price update).\n\nNow I'm looking at the remaining accounts for settle_round and the full structure for timeout_refund, which includes the treasury account that must match config, a rent receiver that must match the round's server field, and remaining accounts for either winner wallets or all players depending on the instruction.\n\nFor timeout_refund, the accounts are the caller as signer, the round PDA to close, config PDA, rent receiver matching the round's server, and remaining accounts for all player wallets.\n\nThe instruction data for all three is straightforward—just the discriminator and round_id, so 16 bytes total for each.\n\nNow I need to set up the implementation by importing the necessary IDL and decoders, deriving the program ID, adding discriminators and PDA helpers, then building out the three transaction builder functions. The key thing I'm realizing is that while the spec describes these as builders only, the settle and timeout functions need to know which accounts to include in remaining_accounts, and the spec indicates the caller passes those account lists as parameters rather than the builder fetching them on-chain. the interface and dependencies. For `buildSettleRoundTx`, I need to figure out what data the caller provides versus what the builder fetches—the winner accounts come from the caller, but I'll need to read the treasury address from the config PDA and the rent receiver from the round account itself.\n\nLooking at the existing settle patterns in the codebase, they fetch the necessary on-chain data within the settle function rather than requiring the caller to pass everything in, so I should follow that same approach here. I'm realizing the builders should stay pure—just accept all necessary accounts and return a Transaction, letting the clock worker handle RPC fetching. But the existing settlement functions do everything at once, so I need to reconcile this with the spec's `build*Tx` naming convention, which clearly indicates these should be builder functions rather than full settlement flows.\n\nI'm settling on having them accept connection and serverKeypair as dependencies along with the specific parameters, returning a signed Transaction. They'll derive PDAs and fetch the config account for treasury internally, but won't touch the database.\n\nDefining the interface...\n\nNow I'm thinking through what each builder needs to fetch versus what can be passed in. For settle_round, I need the treasury from the config PDA, and for timeout_refund, the rent_receiver is just the server keypair's public key. The on-chain program handles authorization validation, so the builders just need to construct the right accounts and let me figure out whether to fetch config or have callers pass treasury as a parameter.\n\nI think the cleanest approach is having the builders accept the resolved accounts as parameters—the clock worker already reads the round on-chain to determine winners, so it can fetch the config for treasury at the same time. This keeps the builders focused on their core job.\n\nDefining the parameter interfaces...\n\nWait, the spec actually specifies exact function signatures like `buildCreateRoundTx(roundId, pythPriceAccount)` and `buildSettleRoundTx(roundId, pythPriceAccount, winnerAccounts)`, so I need to align with those while still following the existing pattern in tx-builder.ts where builders take a params object. Let me check what settle-tx.ts already does to stay consistent.\n\nI see that settle-tx.ts uses SettleTxDeps which includes db, connection, serverKeypair, and entropyAccount, but for closecall I won't need the db or entropyAccount since those are specific to commit-reveal games. I'll define a lighter CloseCallTxDeps with just connection and serverKeypair, then create the three builder functions following that pattern.\n\nDefining the interface and function signatures...\n\nNow I'm realizing that for the settle operation, the rent_receiver should be the server's public key since the server created the round, so I can derive that from the serverKeypair in the deps. I'll use `serverKeypair.publicKey` as the rent receiver since the backend is always the server in our system. Now I need to write the code—importing the closeCall IDL, setting up the discriminators, deriving the PDA, and building the three functions. I should also check whether to export CLOSECALL_PROGRAM_ID from tx-builder.ts or define it elsewhere, following the same pattern as COINFLIP_PROGRAM_ID and LORDOFRNGS_PROGRAM_ID.\n\nWriting the implementation... Still writing the setup code... Building the transaction instruction... Building the instruction accounts... Building the transaction structure... Building the transaction...\n\nActually, I need to verify the account structure for settle_round against the IDL. Looking at the explorer's findings, I see the accounts should be caller, round, config, price_update, treasury, and rent_receiver, followed by remaining accounts—but I'm not sure I have price_update and treasury in my current setup, so let me check what accounts I'm actually passing.\n\nFor timeout_refund, the structure is simpler: just caller, round, config, and rent_receiver. And create_round needs server, config, round, price_update, and system_program.\n\nThe key thing I'm realizing is that rent_receiver must match round.server for the on-chain validation to pass, and since the backend creates the round, that means rent_receiver should be the serverKeypair's public key—which is what I'm using, so that's correct. But I'm still uncertain whether the caller for settle_round needs to be the server or if it can be something else.\n\nActually, looking at this more carefully: the caller doesn't have to be the server for settle_round, but in our system the backend is the one calling it. The rent goes to round.server, not to the caller. So as long as the backend is the signer and round.server matches the serverKeypair's public key (which it does, since the backend created the round), everything lines up.\n\nLet me double-check that the CLOSECALL_PROGRAM_ID matches what's in the IDL.\n\nNow I need to add the ClosecallIDL import to settle-tx.ts alongside the existing imports, and make sure CLOSECALL_PROGRAM_ID is available in tx-builder.ts.\n\nLet me verify the instruction names from the IDL match what I'm using for the discriminator calls—I've got \"create_round\", \"settle_round\", and the timeout refund instruction, which all check out.\n\nNow I'm looking at whether Anchor uses snake_case or camelCase for instruction names in the IDL. The existing code shows `claim_payout` in snake_case, so that's the pattern I should follow, but I want to double-check how Anchor v0.32+ actually generates these names in the IDL JSON. Looking at Anchor 0.32, the IDL JSON actually uses snake_case for instruction names like `create_match` and `claim_payout` because they mirror 